      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Cuvee Lenz Winery, Peconic, 1991. About $20.</p>
        <p>Last things first. This golden-colored medium-bodied sparkling wine has an exceptionally long aftertaste, the hallmark of a well-made wine. But even before the glass is drained and ready for a refill, it is clear that Eric Fry, the wine maker, has released a sophisticated winner.</p>
        <p>The pinot noir grapes (65 percent) and a noticeable yeastiness give the wine a mouth-filling body; the chardonnay (35 percent) provides drive.</p>
        <p>This Cuvee, the first since the 1990 vintage, comes across as virtually bone dry, almost resembling the austere Champagne that the French call naturel. It has been aged on the yeast since September 1992 and is being managed as a so-called recently disgorged product. Numbers of bottles stay on the yeast, gathering complexity, until disgorged for sale.</p>
        <p>Thanks to the refreshing acidity and highly effervescent small bubbles, Cuvee is an aperitif and dinner wine, though I tilt toward use at the table.</p>
        <p>First things last: sip it in a flute so that the tall sides and inward tilt of the upper part of glass can capture and hold the delicate scent. HOWARD G. GOLDBERG</p>
      </block>
